<section class="mt-12 pb-24">
  <h1 class="mb-8 text-2xl font-bold tracking-tight text-gray-900 sm:text-6xl">About Pokémon WiKi</h1>

  <p class="mt-4 text-gray-700">
    Welcome to <strong>Pokémon WiKi</strong>! This website is my Rails Intro Project for the Web Dev 3 course at Red River College.
  </p>

  <h2 class="mt-8 text-xl font-semibold text-gray-900">Project Overview</h2>
  <p class="mt-4 text-gray-700">
    In this project, I used four data sources from the same API to get all the information needed. I used the Gem
    <a href="https://github.com/rdavid1099/poke-api-v2" class="text-blue-500 hover:underline">poke-api-v2</a> to access the data.
  </p>

  <h3 class="mt-6 text-lg font-semibold text-gray-900">Data Source 1: Pokémon</h3>
  <p class="mt-2 text-gray-700">
    This data source gives detailed information about Pokémon, like their abilities, base experience, height, weight, moves, stats, types,
    and more. By default, it returns 20 Pokémon per query, but I can adjust it by adding a "limit" parameter.
  </p>
  <p class="mt-2 text-gray-700">
    I stored this data in a <code>pokemons</code> table in my database. It has the following columns:
  </p>
  <ul class="list-disc list-inside ml-6 mt-2 text-gray-700">
    <li><code>id</code>: Unique identifier for each Pokémon.</li>
    <li><code>name</code>: Name of the Pokémon.</li>
    <li><code>base_experience</code>: The base experience points given when the Pokémon is defeated.</li>
    <li><code>height</code> and <code>weight</code>: Physical size of the Pokémon.</li>
    <li><code>is_default</code>: Indicates if this is the default form of the Pokémon.</li>
    <li><code>order_num</code>: The order for sorting, often used to group families of Pokémon.</li>
    <li><code>type1</code> and <code>type2</code>: The primary and secondary types of the Pokémon.</li>
    <li><code>created_at</code> and <code>updated_at</code>: Timestamps for record tracking.</li>
  </ul>

  <h3 class="mt-6 text-lg font-semibold text-gray-900">Data Source 2: Pokémon Abilities</h3>
  <p class="mt-2 text-gray-700">
    This endpoint gives information about the different abilities that Pokémon can have, including effect entries and flavor text.
  </p>
  <p class="mt-2 text-gray-700">
    I stored this data in an <code>abilities</code> table with the following columns:
  </p>
  <ul class="list-disc list-inside ml-6 mt-2 text-gray-700">
    <li><code>id</code>: Unique identifier for each ability.</li>
    <li><code>name</code>: Name of the ability.</li>
    <li><code>created_at</code> and <code>updated_at</code>: Timestamps.</li>
  </ul>
  <p class="mt-2 text-gray-700">
    To represent the many-to-many relationship between Pokémon and abilities, I created a join table called <code>pokemon_abilities</code>:
  </p>
  <ul class="list-disc list-inside ml-6 mt-2 text-gray-700">
    <li><code>id</code></li>
    <li><code>pokemon_id</code>: References a Pokémon.</li>
    <li><code>ability_id</code>: References an ability.</li>
    <li><code>is_hidden</code>: Indicates if the ability is hidden.</li>
    <li><code>slot</code>: The slot number of the ability.</li>
    <li><code>created_at</code> and <code>updated_at</code></li>
  </ul>

  <h3 class="mt-6 text-lg font-semibold text-gray-900">Data Source 3: Pokémon Moves</h3>
  <p class="mt-2 text-gray-700">
    This data source provides information about the moves that Pokémon can learn, including their power, accuracy, PP (Power Points),
    priority, and type.
  </p>
  <p class="mt-2 text-gray-700">
    I stored this data in a <code>moves</code> table with these columns:
  </p>
  <ul class="list-disc list-inside ml-6 mt-2 text-gray-700">
    <li><code>id</code></li>
    <li><code>name</code></li>
    <li><code>pp</code>: Number of times the move can be used.</li>
    <li><code>priority</code>: Determines the order of move execution.</li>
    <li><code>move_type</code>: The type of the move (e.g., "fire", "water").</li>
    <li><code>created_at</code> and <code>updated_at</code></li>
  </ul>
  <p class="mt-2 text-gray-700">
    The relationship between Pokémon and moves is also many-to-many, represented by the <code>pokemon_moves</code> table:
  </p>
  <ul class="list-disc list-inside ml-6 mt-2 text-gray-700">
    <li><code>id</code></li>
    <li><code>pokemon_id</code></li>
    <li><code>move_id</code></li>
    <li><code>level_learned_at</code>: The level when the Pokémon learns the move.</li>
    <li><code>move_learn_method</code>: How the move is learned (e.g., level-up, TM).</li>
    <li><code>created_at</code> and <code>updated_at</code></li>
  </ul>

  <h3 class="mt-6 text-lg font-semibold text-gray-900">Data Source 4: Pokémon Items</h3>
  <p class="mt-2 text-gray-700">
    This endpoint provides information about items that Pokémon can hold, including their cost, effects, and attributes.
  </p>
  <p class="mt-2 text-gray-700">
    I stored this data in an <code>items</code> table with the following columns:
  </p>
  <ul class="list-disc list-inside ml-6 mt-2 text-gray-700">
    <li><code>id</code></li>
    <li><code>name</code></li>
    <li><code>cost</code>: The purchase price of the item.</li>
    <li><code>fling_power</code>: The item's power when used with the move Fling.</li>
    <li><code>created_at</code> and <code>updated_at</code></li>
  </ul>
  <p class="mt-2 text-gray-700">
    The <code>pokemon_items</code> table represents the many-to-many relationship between Pokémon and items:
  </p>
  <ul class="list-disc list-inside ml-6 mt-2 text-gray-700">
    <li><code>id</code></li>
    <li><code>pokemon_id</code></li>
    <li><code>item_id</code></li>
    <li><code>version</code>: The game version where the item is available.</li>
    <li><code>rarity</code>: How rare the item is.</li>
    <li><code>created_at</code> and <code>updated_at</code></li>
  </ul>

